Some epidemiological studies suggested that HIV-1 transmission between populations in Haiti and the Dominican Republic was uncommon during the early years and that tourists were the most likely source of first virus transmissions to Dominicans (
 Pape et al., 1983; 
 Koenig et al., 1987). Our phylogeographic analysis, however, supports that HIV-1 B
 CAR strains have been disseminated between Haiti and the Dominican Republic since the early 1970s and that several B
 CAR transmission networks were already established in the Dominican Republic by mid-1970s, nearly a decade before the first AIDS cases were officially recognized in the country. The overall time scale here obtained for the B
 CAR epidemic is fully consistent with that recovered in previous studies (
 Gilbert et al., 2007; 
 Junqueira et al., 2011; 
 Cabello et al., 2014; 
 Worobey et al., 2016), supporting the reliability of our T
 MRCA estimates. These results clearly indicate that HIV-1 B
 CAR strains have been disseminated between Haitian and Dominican populations quite frequently since the early 1970s onwards.
